III. First, then, we say, that if the cause of war be unjust, though the war be regular in manner, all acts thence arising are unjust, according to internal injustice. And all who operate knowingly in such acts, 01· co·operate, are in the number of those who cannot enter into the kingdom of heaven without repentance for their acts. Now repent- ance, if time and opportunity be granted, requires restitution. And therefore, God declares that the fastings of those who (Isaiah lviii. 6) do not unloose unjust bonds are not grateful to him. And (Jona'n iii. 8) the king of Nineveh proclaimed a fast, that the people might cease from violence: acknowledging, by a natural impulse, that repentance was idle without such amendment. And such we find the judgment, not only of Christians and Jews, but of Mahomedans.
